Introduction to Section B

Where Section A established the conceptual and methodological foundation of the Vallance Hypothesis, Section B now grounds the inquiry within its historical environment.
To understand how the Turin Shroud’s image could have been produced, we must establish:

its documented appearances,

its gaps in provenance,

the scientific controversies that shaped its interpretation,

and the Renaissance intellectual climate that permitted — or suppressed — optical experimentation.


This section examines the Shroud not as a relic of theological narrative, but as an object moving through time, institutions, and hands, leaving behind a trail of partial records and interpretive disputes.
The purpose is not to assert authorship, but to identify the historical conditions of possibility.

