B — HISTORICAL PROBLEM STATEMENT


---

a. Background to the Shroud Debate

Since its emergence in 14th-century France, the Turin Shroud has occupied a contested intellectual space.
Its dual nature — simultaneously devotional and physical — forced scholars, clergy, and scientists to treat it as both an image and an object.
The debate was shaped by:

the absence of a complete chain of custody,

conflicting testimonies about its origins,

and the unprecedented tonal structure of the image itself.


From the outset, the Shroud defied established categories: it was neither painting, nor bas-relief, nor photograph, nor known textile imprint.
This ambiguity catalysed centuries of dispute, each generation projecting its own interpretive frameworks upon it.


---

b. Chronological Overview (1350–1600)

The earliest secure records date to c. 1357 when Geoffroi de Charny displayed the cloth in Lirey, France.
Subsequent documentation includes episcopal objections, papal toleration, and eyewitness accounts of pilgrim crowds.
Its movements include:

Lirey → Chambéry (Savoy)
Likely transferred through familial inheritance or ducal acquisition.

Chambéry → Turin (1578)
Relocated by the House of Savoy for reasons of prestige, safety, and political consolidation.


The period 1450–1520 — Leonardo’s active years — coincides with an archival gap in the Shroud’s visibility.
This is not evidence of disappearance, but of the era’s fragmentary record-keeping.

This silence constitutes one of the most critical historical variables.


---

c. Scientific Investigations to Date

Three major phases define modern investigation:

1. Photography (1898)
Secondo Pia’s negative plate shocked the academic world, revealing a lifelike positive image.[^1]


2. Instrumentation (1978 STURP)
Multispectral imaging, X-ray fluorescence, and reflectance spectroscopy revealed:

no pigment binder,

no brushstrokes,

and image superficiality confined to fibril tips.[^2]



3. Radiocarbon Dating (1988)
A single sampling corner yielded a medieval date (1260–1390 CE), later challenged due to evidence of:

mixed fibres,

16th-century repair reweaving,

and thermal contamination from the 1532 fire.[^3]




These investigations resolved some questions but deepened others — especially the mechanism of formation.

[^1]: Pia, S. (1898). First photographic negative of the Shroud.
[^2]: STURP Final Report, 1978.
[^3]: Damon et al., Nature, 1989; Rogers, 2005.


